This is a ?T? intersection.  There is a turn pocket northbound, the only purpose for which is to make a u-turn.  It is very rarely used.  Historically, it was only triggered when traffic was in the lane.  Likewise the southbound Morena to eastbound Avati Dr. was an as-needed signal, cycling green only when triggered by presence of a vehicle.  A few months ago(ish), both became regular rotation signals, meaning, they cycle green, regardless of whether there is a vehicle in need of permission to turn/u-turn.  This extends the time N/S- bound traffic is detained at the intersection unnecessarily, particularly given that a single car needing to turn onto southbound Morena from Avati Drive is sufficient to trigger the whole cycle.  I thought the change might be construction related, but, that no longer seems applicable.  Unnecessary stops and extended idling is wasting time and fuel and adding pollutants to the air. service_name: SWPP - Storm Water Polution Prevention Monitoring
public_description: Investigation Details: While conducting an upstream investigation of DW0942 a Major MS4 Outfall, Mayra and I came across 4 locations of interest all related to 10010 Torrey Pines Rd, the Salk Institute for Biological Studies (Figure 1). All are located along Salk Institute Road, east of North Torrey Pines Road. 1. Trash Discharge - Grated inlet to the west of the western driveway on Salk Institute Rd. The grated inlet was dry but was littered with a high volume of cigarette butts. (Figure 2 and 3). 2. Water Discharge - Grated inlet on the eastern side of the western driveway. Here there was a PVC pipe that entered from the north that was flowing at a rate of approximately 0.3 gallons per minute. We were unable to remove the grated inlet and the slits were too narrow to take any samples. The upstream portions of this system are not mapped and are likely private. Photos taken at this location were lost. 3. Water Discharge - Grated inlet on the eastern side of the western building near the handicap and deliveries driveway. Here there was a PVC pipe that entered from the north that was flowing at a rate of approximately 0.1 gallons per minute. We were unable to remove the grated inlet and the slits were too narrow to take any samples. The upstream portions of this system are not mapped and are likely private. Photos taken at this location were lost. 4. Inquire - Manhole in the grass between the eastern most driveway cutouts on Salk Institute Rd. Here the manhole was ajar with some equipment nearby. As we did not know what this setup was we did not attempt to move or open the manhole or equipment. The downstream location where this structure is mapped to drain to was dry. There does not appear to be a discharge here, but more information regarding what this setup was would be beneficial. (Figure 4).

Since pedestrians coming down the stairs from the west may not be at all visible to motorists heading south, until right before pedestrians enter the road, I think it's important that the stenciling on the road be redone so as to make it more obvious that there's a stop sign/crosswalk. Some motorists just blow through that section of Bachman without realizing they need to stop, which is dangerous for pedestrians.
